Regression problem¶

By: Thu Nguyen

Note: This is the outcome of my coursework project in the Machine Learning Class.

1. Introduction¶

In this project, I will build and optimise (fine-tune) a regression model to predict the popularity of songs. Features of each song include "title", "artist", "top genre", "year", "bpm", "nrgy", "dnce", "dB", "live", "val", "dur", "cous", "spch". The ouput (predicted) value is the popularity of songs which is stored in column named "pop". The data has 3 non-numeric attributes, Id column, and 11 numeric attributes as seen in the picture below.

To build the final regression model, following steps were conducted:

1 - Data exploration

  • In this step, besides detecting missing data, and outliers, I tried to analyze object features to see if one hot encoding could be used to transform non-numeric features into numeric data, which can be useful for regression modeling.

2 - Data visualisation

  • In this step, I tried to visualise and define potential linear or non-linear relationships between "pop" and other features. I combined scatter plots and regression lines with different degrees, whereby I discovered two variables that could have a non-linear relationship with pop.

3 - Data preparation

  • The data preparation step has been done with standard steps including cleaning data, adding necessary variables, and scaling data. Due to the training dataset is small, before removing outliers, I compared the performance of the trained models with the cleaned dataset and the unclean dataset to ensure that cleaning is necessary. Data cleaning has been proven effective. However, in this notebook, I show only the works related to the clean data.

4 - Build and Fine-tune the best regression model

  • Finally, when the data was ready, different regression models including LinearRegression, LinearSVR, DecisionTreeRegressor and RandomForestRegressor are built. In addition, I also used two ensemble learning techniques (Soft voting, Ada boosting) to improve model scores. The model with minimum RMSE is chosen as the best model. Beside, I also tried the Gradient Boosting and stacking methods but the model's improvement was not found. Therefore, the Gradient Boosting and stacking methods are not included in this notebook.

The detailed explaination will be covered in the description of each code cell.

As you can see, there are 81 different categories in 'top genre' column, 317 different artists in the 'artist' column, and 405 titles in the 'title' column. If I use OneHotEncoder to convert these columns to numerical (binary) data, I will have to many columns. Meanwhile, the dataframe has only 407 instances.

On the other hand, I do not want to use ordinal_encoder since it may impose some un-wanted relationships between categories.

Therefore, I will not use these three columns for building regression models. As a result, 10 NAN values in 'top genre' column will not cause any issue since this column will be excluded.

Moreover, there are two titles: "Take Good Care Of My Baby - 1990 Remastered" and "Please Mr. Postman" that are repeated twice in the dataset. We will try to deal with this issue in the prepare data section.

In fact, I tried many times for both linear and non-linear assumptions with different degrees. These plots below are the best options.

In [71]:
def plot_pop_vs_others(df, col_name, relation_degree, i):
    df2 = df.copy()
    df2 = df2.sort_values(by=[col_name])

    Xplot = df2[col_name]
    
    plt.subplot(3,3,i+1)
    z = np.polyfit(Xplot, df2['pop'], relation_degree)
    p = np.poly1d(z)
    plt.scatter(Xplot, df2['pop'], s=10)
    plt.plot(Xplot, p(Xplot), c='r', ls='-')
In [72]:
plt.rc('font', size = 12)

cols2 = ['bpm','nrgy','dnce','dB','live','dur','acous','spch','age']
for i in range(len(cols2)):
    col_name = cols2[i]
    if (col_name=='dur') | (col_name=='age'):
        relation_degree = 2
    else:
        relation_degree = 1
        
    plot_pop_vs_others(df, col_name, relation_degree, i)

Base on the correlation coefficients and plots, I can see that "dur" & "age" may have non-linear relations with "pop". The other attributes may have the potential linear relationships with "pop".

d) Remove outliers by using DBSCAN clustering¶

In addition to removing manually base on the box plot in the previous step, I will use clustering technique to detect anormal data points which can be considered as outliers which need to be removed. As I can see in the plots in Section 4.1 and 4.2, the data distributions are not really spherical. Therefore, DBSCAN clustering is chosen.

The value of parameter "eps" in each clustering will be adjusted according to the density of the scatter plots observed in Section 4. In general, I use a very large value for "eps" to avoid removal of too many data points.

In [78]:
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN

print("Data shape before removing outliers using DBSCAN clustering: ", df.shape)

## clustering for a sub-dataframe with only two columns: 'pop' and 'acous'
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=9, min_samples=5)
dbscan.fit(df[['acous', 'pop']])
# dbscan.labels_
df = df.loc[dbscan.labels_!=-1]

## clustering for a sub-dataframe with only two columns: 'pop' and 'dur'
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=15, min_samples=5)
dbscan.fit(df[['dur', 'pop']])
# dbscan.labels_
df = df.loc[dbscan.labels_!=-1]

## clustering for a sub-dataframe with only two columns: 'pop' and 'nrgy'
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=10, min_samples=5)
dbscan.fit(df[['nrgy', 'pop']])
# dbscan.labels_
df = df.loc[dbscan.labels_!=-1]

## clustering for a sub-dataframe with only two columns: 'pop' and 'dnce'
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=10, min_samples=5)
dbscan.fit(df[['dnce', 'pop']])
# dbscan.labels_
df = df.loc[dbscan.labels_!=-1]

## clustering for a sub-dataframe with only two columns: 'pop' and 'age'
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=10, min_samples=5)
dbscan.fit(df[['age', 'pop']])
# dbscan.labels_
df = df.loc[dbscan.labels_!=-1]

df = df.reset_index(drop=True)
print("Data shape after removing outliers using DBSCAN clustering: ", df.shape)

Data shape before removing outliers using DBSCAN clustering:  (401, 11)

6.1. Train and Fine-Tune Individual Model¶

First, I will try four different regression models including: LinearRegression, LinearSVR, DecisionTreeRegressor and RandomForestRegressor. The best model will be determined by using following steps:

  • Step 1: Fine-Tune individual models using GridSearchCV to obtain the best parameters for individual models
  • Step 2: Use Ensemble Learning including Soft voting, Ada boosting to improve model scores
  • Step 3: Determine the best (final) model based on RMSE score when predict test set

During training, the cross validation technique with cv=5 is used to split data into 5 folds. The best paramters will be used for training the optimised model.

6.1.1. Linear Regression¶

In [84]:
lin_reg = LinearRegression()

scores = cross_val_score(lin_reg, X_train, y,scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=5)
lin_reg_rmse_scores = np.sqrt(-scores)
print(lin_reg_rmse_scores.mean())

lin_reg.fit(X_train, y)

6.1.2. Fine-Tune Support Vector Regression Model¶

The tolerance 'tol' of the LinearSVR model is set equal to 1e-5, and a gridsearch for 'loss' parameter is conducted.

In [85]:
svm_reg = LinearSVR(tol=1e-5)

param_grid = {'loss': ['epsilon_insensitive', 'squared_epsilon_insensitive']}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(svm_reg, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',return_train_score=True)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y)
best_para = grid_search.best_params_

## optimised SVR model:
svm_reg = LinearSVR(tol=1e-5, loss = best_para['loss'])

scores = cross_val_score(svm_reg, X_train, y, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=5)
svm_reg_rmse_scores = np.sqrt(-scores)
print(svm_reg_rmse_scores.mean())

6.1.4. Fine-Tune Random Forest Model¶

Three parameters: 'n_estimators', 'max_features' and 'bootstrap' are used for the gridsearch.

Compared to the other regression models, the Random Forest model requires a significantly longer time to train. However, the Random Forest model is generally give very good score, slightly better than the individual models above when make prediction for test set.

6.2. Ensemble Learning¶

As the next step, we will use soft voting and Ada boosting methods to improve the models' performances.

6.2.1. Soft voting for the best individual models¶

By trying different model combinations, we found that soft-voting model of three individual models including 'lin_reg', 'forest_reg' and 'svm_reg' give the higher score than the soft-voting model of all four idividual models. It is because the Decision Tree Regression Model has very low score compared to the others. Therefore, as shown in section below, we only conduct soft voting for three models:

In [88]:
from sklearn.ensemble import VotingRegressor

soft_voting = VotingRegressor(estimators=[('lr', lin_reg), ('forest', forest_reg), ('svm', svm_reg)])

scores = cross_val_score(soft_voting, X_train, y, scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=5)
soft_voting_rmse_scores = np.sqrt(-scores)
print(soft_voting_rmse_scores.mean())

soft_voting.fit(X_train, y)

9.637025631362913
Out[88]:
VotingRegressor(estimators=[('lr', LinearRegression()),
                            ('forest',
                             RandomForestRegressor(max_features='log2')),
                            ('svm',
                             LinearSVR(loss='squared_epsilon_insensitive',
                                       tol=1e-05))])

Now, let's use these model to make predictions for the test set.

First, I need to conduct the same operations that I did for training set. These operations include converting year to age, removing 'year', 'title', 'artist', 'top genre' columns, and adding 'age2' and 'dur2' columns as belows:

In [91]:
df_test = pd.read_csv('CS98XRegression_Test.csv')
y_test = df_test['pop']

today = date.today()
df_test['age'] = today.year - df_test['year']

df_test = df_test.drop(['year', 'title', 'artist', 'top genre'], axis=1)
df_test['age2'] = df_test['age']**2
df_test['dur2'] = df_test['dur']**2

X_test = autoscaler.fit_transform(df_test[features])

Now, let's make prediction:

In [92]:
